Repeated-Measures ANOVA

Our measure for dilution: Difference between first and last link.

8-links chain contrast:

# contrast 1st vs. 8th link 

tdata_18 <- subset(tdata_8links, variable == "1st" | variable == "8th")
tdata_sub <- tdata_18

a1 <- aov_car(value ~ variable + Error(sID/(variable)), tdata_sub)

# contrast

ls2 <- lsmeans(a1, c("variable")) # group means by between-condition
ls2
##  variable lsmean    SE  df lower.CL upper.CL
##  X1st      0.723 0.028 178    0.668    0.779
##  X8th      0.595 0.028 178    0.539    0.650
## 
## Warning: EMMs are biased unless design is perfectly balanced 
## Confidence level used: 0.95
# simple main effects 
t <- pairs(ls2) # compares rep-measure differences separately for each between-factor level
t
##  contrast    estimate     SE df t.ratio p.value
##  X1st - X8th    0.129 0.0323 99 3.989   0.0001

Yes, the contrast is significant (see contrast output).

Compute a 95 CI for the difference:

confint(t, adjust = "none")
##  contrast    estimate     SE df lower.CL upper.CL
##  X1st - X8th    0.129 0.0323 99   0.0647    0.193
## 
## Confidence level used: 0.95

Manually:

t <- qt(0.975, 99, lower.tail = TRUE, log.p = FALSE) # get the correct t-Value


effect <- "Mdiff"
Mdiff <- 0.129  # the estimated difference from the output above
SE <- 0.0323  # its SE 
CI <- SE*t
CI_low <- Mdiff - CI
CI_up <- Mdiff + CI

Mdiff

CI_low
## [1] 0.06490979

What Cohens d does this difference correspond to?

tdata_18$variable <- factor(tdata_18$variable, levels = c("1st", "8th"))


library(effsize)
cohen.d(tdata_18$value,tdata_18$variable, paired = T)
## 
## Cohen's d
## 
## d estimate: 0.4589207 (small)
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##     lower     upper 
## 0.2203860 0.6974555

Get SE for d

d <- 0.4589207

dat_1st <- subset(tdata_18, variable == "1st")
dat_8th <- subset(tdata_18, variable == "8th")

cor.test(dat_1st$value, dat_8th$value)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  dat_1st$value and dat_8th$value
## t = 3.5569, df = 98, p-value = 0.0005801
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.1517979 0.5012608
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.3381342
cor <- 0.3381342 
n <- 100

SEd <- sqrt((1/n + d^2/n)*2*(1-cor))
SEd
## [1] 0.1265907
